4 After trying the some of the more popular AYCE sushi joints around Vegas, I grew tired of frequenting the same places kinds of places over and over again. I decided to peek through a few yelp suggestions and stumbled upon this place.  Just off of the 215 and eastern, at the extravagant Wal-Mart shopping center, is Sin City Sushi. It's not the best looking of places from the outside, but the inside is more accommodating. It's nothing crazy fancy. It's simple, clean and gets the job done.  We got there at 9:50pm, saw the sign stating they close at 10pm, and decided to turn around to our cars. The manager came out and told us that they were still open, despite what the sign said. Furthermore, he let us know that they plan to extend the weekend hours in next week or so. With that said, we went inside to start our feast in the seemingly empty restaurant. Fellow Yelpers said the place was good, so why not?  We ordered every single item that was recommended from the waitress, ranging from apps, nigiri, rolls and dessert. They had a good amount of specialty rolls which took up the both sides of the given AYCE menu. We dabbled into ordering to whatever sounded good. For starters we had the baked green mussels, oyster shooters and baby tako. Pretty good stuff, especially the tako. Nigiri was pretty basic.. dry in some cases. I wouldn't recommend going here for the nigiri. Recommendations for specialty rolls were the Sin City Roll and the Wet Dream. Of the two, the Wet Dream was our favorite, though a bit embarrassing to order. The other rolls we ordered were nothing memorable, but satisfying nonetheless.  For dessert, they let you finish off with either ice cream or mochi, each with various flavors. Pretty standard fare.  Service was very intimate due to us being the only ones in there. We had a great chat with the manager and waitress while eating. Service was top notch, even though we felt like we were holding them up for eating past closing time. They insisted that we come in, so I guess it wasn't too big a problem. They seemed generally pleased that we were there to eat. We were treated like people in there, unlike the more popular busy AYCE places in which you are shooed in, then shooed out within a 60 minute time frame. That kind of friendly service was enough for us to come back.  Food: 3 1/2 stars Service: 5 stars Value: $25 for AYCE dinner
